			<div class="blog-post-meta">
				<p class="meta-info">Published April 15, 2026 · By the Sula Catering Team</p>
			</div>

			<p>Planning an Indian wedding in Vancouver means juggling more than just one event — it's a multi-day celebration spanning sangeet, mehndi, ceremony, and reception, each with its own menu, mood, and logistics. After fifteen years of catering hundreds of South Asian weddings across the Lower Mainland, we've learned what makes the difference between a stressful planning process and one that flows. This guide pulls together everything we wish every couple knew before they started.</p>

			<h2>Start with the <em>Guest Count</em></h2>

			<p>Before menus, before vendors, before tastings — the guest count drives every other decision. South Asian weddings in Vancouver typically range from 200 to 500 guests, and that scale changes which venues you can book, which catering formats work, and how far in advance you need to lock in dates.</p>

			<p>For peak wedding season (May through October), we recommend booking your caterer at least six to nine months in advance. Off-peak dates have more flexibility, but the most in-demand caterers still book up quickly.</p>

			<h2>Plan Each Event <em>Separately</em></h2>

			<p>An Indian wedding is really three to four events stacked together. Each one needs its own thinking:</p>

			<h3>Sangeet & Mehndi</h3>
			<p>These pre-wedding events lean into atmosphere and energy. Live cooking stations work beautifully here — chaat counters, dosa stations, kebab grills. Guests are mingling, music is playing, and food becomes part of the experience rather than a sit-down moment. We typically recommend lighter portions, more variety, and stations that let guests interact with the food.</p>

			<h3>Ceremony Lunch</h3>
			<p>Ceremony catering is often more traditional — pure-vegetarian thalis, Jain-friendly options, regional specialties that reflect the families' heritage. This is the meal where dietary restrictions matter most. Plan for separate vegetarian and Jain stations if both communities are represented.</p>

			<h3>Reception Dinner</h3>
			<p>The reception is where most couples invest the largest portion of the catering budget. Plated dinners or premium buffets, halal-certified meats, full bar pairings, dessert spreads, and often a late-night chaat or coffee station to keep the energy going.</p>

			<h2>Halal, Vegetarian, Vegan, <em>Jain</em></h2>

			<p>One of the biggest challenges in South Asian wedding catering is honouring multiple dietary requirements without compromising on any of them. At Sula, we maintain dedicated kitchen areas to prepare Jain and pure-vegetarian dishes separately from non-vegetarian preparations. All chicken and lamb is halal-certified through trusted local BC suppliers.</p>

			<p>When you meet with your caterer, ask explicitly:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Are halal meats sourced from certified suppliers?</li>
				<li>Are Jain dishes prepared in a separate kitchen area?</li>
				<li>How are allergens (especially nuts and dairy) labelled and tracked?</li>
				<li>Are vegan and gluten-free options part of the standard menu, or do they require advance notice?</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Build the Menu <em>With Your Chef</em></h2>

			<p>Pre-set menu packages work for some couples — but most South Asian weddings benefit from a custom-built menu. Schedule a meeting with the head chef early in the process. Bring family favourites, regional specialties from both sides, and any dishes with sentimental meaning. A good caterer will weave these into the menu rather than forcing you into a fixed package.</p>

			<p>For weddings of 100+ guests, a tasting is standard. We recommend doing the tasting after the menu is largely defined, then using it to fine-tune spice levels, plating, and final selections.</p>

			<h2>Logistics That Make or <em>Break the Day</em></h2>

			<p>The food can be perfect and the wedding can still feel chaotic if logistics aren't handled. Here's what to confirm before signing a contract:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Setup and breakdown times — how early does the team arrive?</li>
				<li>Number of servers and chefs on-site</li>
				<li>Equipment needs — chafing dishes, induction burners, serving platters</li>
				<li>Power and water access at the venue</li>
				<li>Buffet vs. plated service flow</li>
				<li>Coordination with other vendors (DJ, planner, decor)</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The <em>Coordinator</em></h2>

			<p>This is the single most important person in your catering experience. A dedicated coordinator should handle everything from your first email to the final cleanup — your point person for menus, timeline, day-of logistics, and any last-minute changes. If a caterer doesn't assign a dedicated coordinator, that's a red flag for a wedding of any meaningful size.</p>

			<h2>Budget <em>Realistically</em></h2>

			<p>Indian wedding catering in Vancouver typically runs from $60 to $150+ per guest depending on menu complexity, service style, and add-ons like live stations or premium bar service. For a 300-guest wedding with sangeet and reception, expect total catering costs in the $30,000–$60,000 range. Budget extra for tastings, gratuity, taxes, and overtime if events run long.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

			<p>The right caterer doesn't just feed your guests — they hold the day together. They handle the timeline. They manage the kitchen. They keep the buffet flowing. They quietly solve problems before you ever see them.</p>

